[4] France (Ile-de-France)
Date: Tue 13 Nov 2018
Source: The Connexion (France) [abridged, edited]
https://www.connexionfrance.com/French-news/Ile-de-France-Measles-outbreak-due-to-lack-of-vaccination-coverage-say-doctors


A serious measles outbreak is spreading across the Ile-de-France region, which doctors say is due to a lack of vaccination coverage among the general population. Whereas the usual rate of diagnosis averages about 1 case per week in the region, 56 cases were diagnosed in October 2018 alone.

In the worst-affected area, Seine-Saint-Denis, 11 people have been hospitalised due to the disease. Most were children aged 4 and under, whose vaccination records were not up to date. The disease is 10 times more contagious than flu, and it is passed between people by air droplets (such as a cough or sneeze) or by direct contact, such as touching. One ill child in a public space -- such as a crèche -- can infect up to 20-50 others.

In France, doctors must report any diagnosis of measles to their regional branch of medical agency (Agences Régionales de Santé; ARS). No deaths have so far been reported in this recent outbreak, but at the beginning of the year [2018], 3 people died from the condition. The ARS has said that the reappearance of the disease is almost certainly due to a lack of vaccination coverage across France. National coverage needs to be at 95% to prevent outbreaks, it said, but the current level is at 79%. A 95% coverage would protect very young babies, older people, and anyone else who is immunocompromised and cannot themselves receive the jab.

Dr Sylvie Hubinois, paediatrician and president of l'Association Française de Pédiatrie Ambulatoire [the French Association of Ambulatory Paediatrics], said: "This [recent outbreak] is because vaccination coverage is not high enough to be effective. Even though vaccination coverage is rising every year, to avoid epidemics we must reach a very high coverage rate, in the region of 95%. Despite this, no region in France has so far reached such a target." The measles vaccination is now one of the 11 jabs that are now mandatory in France, so experts expect coverage to rise slowly over the next few years.

Between 6 Nov 2017, and August 2018, 2471 cases were reported in France, of which 22% were hospitalised. Dr Hubinois added: "Measles is still a fatal disease. These are preventable deaths. The illness could be eradicated if everyone [that could be] was vaccinated."

This year [2018], the World Health Organisation (WHO) warned of the continued risk of measles, as cases of the disease reached record-breaking levels this year.

